        "lat": "281.— Cambyses expeditionem in Aethiopas facere constituit. Itaque speculatores misit nonnullos ex Ichthyopbagis, qui Aethiopum sermone callebant. Hos ad Aethiopas misit, edoctos quid dicere deberent, et dona ferentes, pallium, armillas aureas, et vini utrem. Dicuntur autem hi Aethiopes fortissimi et pulcherrimi esse omnium hominum: quemcunque etiam ex iis pulcherrimum et corporis viribus praestantissimum indicant, hunc regem faciunt. Ad hos igitur homines ubi advenerunt Icthyophagi, haec verba fecerunt: ‘Cambyses Persarum rex, tecum hospitium, o rex, iungere cupiens, nos misit, et dona tibi haec dat, quorum usu et ipse maxime delectatur.’",
        "eng": "281.— Cambyses decided to make an expedition against the Aethiopians. Therefore, he sent spies composed of some of the Ichthyophagi, who understood the language of the Aethiopians. He sent them to the Aethiopians, instructed on what they should say, and bearing gifts, a cloak, gold bracelets, and a wineskin. These Aethiopians are said to be the strongest and most beautiful of all men: and they choose as king the one they deem the most beautiful and strongest in body. When the Ichthyophagi arrived at these men, they said these words: 'Cambyses, king of the Persians, desiring to form friendship with you, O king, has sent us, and he gives these gifts to you, which he himself enjoys most.'"
